  "opinion": "As a plumber who's been working in Chicago for over forty years, I've seen how people's views on healthcare can shift like a pipe that's been clogged for too long. I don't use social media, so I've never had to navigate the digital noise about vaccines. My kids were young when the pandemic hit, and I remember my daughter telling me she was scared of the shots. I tried to explain it to her using simple terms about how the body fights germs, just like how a pipe gets clogged and needs cleaning. My parents taught me to respect others' beliefs, even when they're different from mine, so I've always tried to listen without judgment. I've found that when people are worried about vaccines, it's often because they're scared of the unknown. I've seen this in my community—neighbors who were hesitant because they thought the vaccines were too new. But I've also seen how important it is to get people to understand that vaccines are like a shield against illness, just like how a good sealant prevents leaks in a pipe. I've tried to help by sharing stories from my own experience, like how I've had to fix pipes that were leaking because of poor maintenance, and how it's better to have a system that works than to let things get worse. I don't think the best way to manage these discussions is to argue or to be confrontational; instead, it's about being patient and understanding. I've learned that when people feel heard, they're more likely to open up and share their concerns. I've also found that it's important to keep things simple and avoid jargon so that everyone can understand. My faith as a Christian has taught me to be compassionate and to seek the common good, so I try to approach these conversations with that mindset in mind.",
